The error means `find` returned `undefined`, and you're trying to read `.name` on it. Either the user with that id doesn't exist, or your comparison is off (string vs number, case sensitivity, etc.). Two safe patterns:

```js
// 1. Optional chaining — returns undefined instead of throwing
return data.users.find(u => u.id === id)?.name;

// 2. Explicit check
const user = data.users.find(u => u.id === id);
if (!user) return null;
return user.name;
```

If you actually want the function to throw when the user is missing, the right place is an explicit guard, not a silent crash on `.name`.
